I route**: I should add `/api/projects/{name}/runs` endpoint for consistency, though the internal API could stay as-is since it's not user-facing.\n\nThe simplest approach is to have `handleProjectRuns` render the runs page directly without redirecting, add backward compatibility by redirecting `/runs?project=X` to the clean URL, update the JavaScript filter function to use the new path structure, and add the corresponding API endpoint.\n\nFor the template, I need to pass both the directory path (for API calls) and the label (for URL navigation) so the JavaScript can construct the proper URLs.\n\nI need to think about how to get the label mapping into the JavaScript. The template currently has access to the project directory through `ProjectFilter`, but I need the label too. I could either pass it directly in the template context or have the JavaScript look it up from the dropdown options.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to keep the API simple - it can still use the directory path internally since it's not user-facing. The HTML URLs should use the clean `/projects/<label>/runs` format. The template needs both pieces of information to make this work properly.\n\nNow I'm planning out the actual changes needed. I should update the handler to render the runs page directly instead of redirecting, add a redirect from the old query parameter style to the new clean URLs, and create a new API endpoint that accepts the project name for consistency.\n\nFor the template, I need to figure out whether to switch the dropdown to use project labels instead of directory paths, or keep the paths but add a mapping layer in JavaScript to handle the URL navigation properly. dir→label\n\nOption (b) seems simpler. Let me pass a `ProjectLabelMap` (JSON map of dir→label) to the template so JS can look up labels.\n\nActually wait - I need to also think about the \"All projects\" case. When no project is selected, the URL is just `/runs`. That should stay the same.\n\nLet me also think about what data `handleProjectRuns` needs. It needs:\n- The project label (from URL path)\n- The project dir (resolved from label)\n- All the same data as `handleRunsList` but pre-filtered\n\nI'll refactor to extract the common logic.\n\nLet me also think about `ProjectFilter` in the template data. Currently it's a directory path. I should add a `ProjectLabel` field (or change `ProjectFilter` to be the label since the URL now uses the label).\n\nActually, the simplest approach: In the template data, pass both `ProjectFilter` (dir, for API calls) and `ProjectFilterLabel` (label, for URL construction). The dropdown values stay as dirs. The JS `filterByProject` function gets a mapping of dir→label.\n\nNow I'm planning the handler changes: I need to add a new route for `/api/projects/{name}/runs`, create a handler that renders the runs page directly, and update the existing handlers to redirect when a project parameter is present. To avoid duplication, I should extract the common logic between the list and project-specific handlers.\n\nRefactoring the code...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2192,"cache_read_input_tokens":33287,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2192},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"abc320af-34b7-429f-bd37-e8e770017e8e","uuid":"22cb3c63-82e7-4e35-bf73-1ab168655d47"}
